Trap inheritable functions

TRAP is the generic trap inheritable.  It inherits TREASURE and
all of its functions.  (Do not use set_short or set_long unless
you set a custom search function, however; this is set up with
the idea that the typical trap is hidden until triggered.)

In addition, TRAP has the following functions:

set_trap_message(string)
set_trap_mess(string)
    Sets the custom message a victim sees when he trips the trap.

set_trap_message2(string)
set_trap_mess2(string)
    Sets the custom message the rest of the room sees when a
    victim trips the trap.

set_setter(object)
    Sets the person who set the trap, if any.  This person has a
    100% chance to find or disarm his trap, and can pass it without
    setting it off, by default.  If the trap does damage, it is also
    credited to this person.

query_setter()
    Returns the setter, if any.

set_damage(int)
    The amount of damage the trap causes, if any.

set_damage_type(int)
    The type of damage the trap causes.  If damage is set but
    damage type is not, this defaults to WEAPON_DAM_MASK.

set_ignore_armor(int)
    Sets whether or not the trap's damage ignores armor.  Set to
    1 if it does, 0 otherwise.  Defaults to 0.  (Useful for poison
    gas, etc.)

set_trigger_action(string)
    Sets the verb which will trip the trap, ie. 'north', or 'pull',
    or 'search'.  This -must- be set, or the trap will never be
    tripped!

add_trigger_action(string)
    Performs the same function as set_trigger_action.

set_trigger_actions(array of strings)
    Sets the verbs which will trip the trap.  Both this function
    and the above two will add to the array of verbs, rather than
    replace them, so which you use is up to you.

set_trigger_object(string)
    Sets the object which will trigger the trap, if any.  If the
    trap is triggered by 'north', this will be blank.  If it's
    triggered by 'pull lever', the trigger_action will be 'pull'
    and the trigger_object will be 'lever'.  If it's triggered by
    'search skeleton', the trigger_action is 'search' and the
    trigger_object is 'skeleton'.  Performing the trigger action
    on a different object, such as 'search for traps' in the third
    example above, will NOT set off the trap.

add_trigger_object(string)
    Performs the same function as set_trigger_object.

set_trigger_objects(array of strings)
    Performs the same function as the above two, but with an array
    of strings instead of one string at a time.

query_trigger()
    Returns the string(s) which must be performed to trigger the
    trap.  (trigger_actions, plus trigger_objects if applicable)

query_triggers()
   Returns the same thing as query_trigger.

set_trap_func(closure)
    If you would like the trap to do something other than damage,
    this function specifies the function to be called when the
    trap is triggered.  It can also be used in addition to the
    damage functions.

set_search_func(closure)
    If you would like to set a customized search procedure, this
    function specifies the function to be called.  The default
    search function is based on int, with thieves and (to a lesser
    extent) bards having a much better chance than other classes.
    Mages and necros also have a much better chance, but only if
    the trap is magical (see below).

set_search_difficulty(int)
    Subtracts int from the chance of successfully searching (using
    the default search function).  Used for traps that are particularly
    difficult or easy to detect.  Note that there is a minimum chance
    of 1%, and a maximum of 95%, in any case.

query_search_difficulty()
    Returns the search difficulty.

set_disarm_difficulty(int)
    Subtracts int from the chance of successfully disarming the
    trap.  The default is based on int and dex, and favors
    thieves, bards, mages, and necros in much the same way as
    the default search function.  Again there is a minimum chance
    of 1% and a maximum of 95%.  (However, the setter can always
    disarm his own trap.)

query_disarm_difficulty()
    Returns the disarm difficulty.

set_trap_type(int)
    Set to 1 if the trap is magical, 0 if it's mechanical.  This
    affects the default search function and the disarm function,
    and also sets the treasure_type to either TYP_MAGIC or
    TYP_FURNITURE, respectively.

remove_trap()
    Call this to destruct the trap.  Included in case of trap-
    removing uniques or the like.

In addition, there are two attributes that apply to traps:
"auto_detect_traps"
    Gives the player a 100% chance of finding the trap (with the
    default search function).  Useful for a 'find traps' spell
    or item.

"immunity_to_traps"
    If the player has this, the trap will trigger without harming
    him.

A trap can be found with the commands 'search', 'find', or
'detect', and the arguments 'traps', 'trap', 'for traps',
or 'for trap'.  It can be disabled with the commands
'disarm', 'remove', or 'disable' and the arguments 'trap'
or 'traps', but only if the person attempting to
disable the trap first succeeded in searching for it.
The default search function displays the trigger on
a successful search and tells the character that
they can attempt to 'disable trap'.
